content.description: Fantastic sustained movement leads through the double overhangs to easier but still engaging climbing higher up. At least two options exist for the intimidating exit mantle.
content.location: Next bolted line to the right of Ataxi crack, trends up and left through the obvious overhangs.

content.description: Route follows multiple flakes, starting with a blocky flake trending rightward. Traverses left after the 5th bolt and then straight up after the 7th bolt. The anchor for the route to the left is visible, near the top, but the correct anchor is straight up a final section.
content.location: On the right-ish end of the crag starting on a small ledge with a large flake.

content.description: For most, this will be the warmup for the wall.   Crux is towards the end and is VERY well protected.
content.location: Exquisite textured rock leads off of a large block and the far left of VVW.  Belay either from the block or from down and climber's left.  IMO, the block provides a nice perch.  With little difficulty I was able to throw a TR on the anchors for the 11d to the right.

content.description: Uh, ok but kind of circuitous.  Also, tends to promote serious rope drag, climbing past a few suspicious blocks.  Best cleaned on TR I think.

climbs.name: My Sorrow Bleeds With Such Delight

content.description:
2 distinct crux sections.  This route is honestly one of the best of its kind around.  Perfect edges and rock make this route a must do.  The only detraction is the start which can be marginalized by stepping left a couple feet and using the large block.  But, the meat is after this, so whatever.

I'm around 5'.  The route is definitely reach dependent and I'd say more 12a.
content.location: Obvious line of bolts just left of the crack and the first route as one hikes up to the crag.

content.description:
This route is BOSS and would be uber popular at areas like Little Si if it were transplanted.  But, with the hike, I'm not sure it has been climbed more than a few times in its 15 year existence.

Steep rock leads up a clean face of varied and mostly positive holds through several baffling sequences.  The Topout is CLASSIC.  So GOOD.

Felt like 12b to me.
Obvious diagonal slightly overhanging crack.  Starts kind of thin.
content.protection: Standard rack, one bolt, chain anchors.

climbs.name: Cascadia Crack
climbs.fa: Leland Windham, Dave Whitelaw, David Wolfe 5/2005

content.description: Start with good fingerlocks, crimps and gastons, cop a couple handjams into off fingers. Keep the pump at bay and hold on to the chains. This is a pure splitter and would be a 4 star climb in Index. Rock quality is the best I've found in N Bend
content.protection: Single rack from .2-#3 BD sizes to make it safe. Could use doubles, and an optional #4 to really sew it up
content.location: Far right side of the wall. Bottom 3/4's stay in the shade all day.

content.description: Haven't done this, but judging from terra firma, the crux comes within the first 20 feet.  Doesn't look too heinous to protect and I'll bet its as fun as reported.
content.protection: Gear.  Widgets and stuff. to 2 or 3 inches.
